shire, England":"Stretton, Staffordshire, England","England":"England, United Kingdom","Stretton by Burton upon Trent, Staffordshire, England":"Stretton by Burton upon Trent, Staffordshire, England, United Kingdom","Birdstone, Herefordshire, England":"Herefordshire, England, United Kingdom","Herefordshire, England":"Herefordshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Higgins","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Irish: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó hUiginn</b> ‘descendant of <i>Uiginn</i>’, a byname meaning ‘viking, sea-rover’ (from Old Norse <i>víkingr</i>). Compare   McGuigan  .","English (Lancashire and Yorkshire): variant of <b>Higgin</b>, itself either a Lancashire variant of <b>Huggin</b> (from a pet form of   Hugh  ), or a variant of   Hickin   (from a pet form of   Richard  ), with genitival or post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>. See   Hick   and compare   Higson  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Higgens","meanings":["English (Kent): variant of   Higgins  ."]},{"name":"McGuigan","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Brendan, Liam, Mairead.","Irish (northern): perhaps an Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mag Uiginn</b> ‘son of the viking’ (see   Higgins   1).","Irish (northern): Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac Guagáin</b>, a shortened form of <b>Mag Eochagáin</b>, son of <i>Eochagán</i>, a diminutive of <i>Eochaidh</i> ‘horseman’. Compare   Geoghegan  ."]},{"name":"Haggins","meanings":["Scottish variant of Irish   Higgins  ."]},{"name":"Heggins","meanings":["Scottish: variant of   Higgins   1."]},{"name":"Kiggins","meanings":["Irish (Galway and Mayo) and Manx: shortened Anglicized form (with English excrescent <i>-s</i>) of Gaelic <b>Mag Uiginn</b> ‘son of the Viking’ (see   Higgins  )."]}]},{"name":"Charles","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From a Germanic word, <i>karl</i>, meaning ‘free man’, akin to Old English <i>ceorl</i> ‘man’. The name, Latin form <i>Carolus</i>, owed its popularity in medieval Europe to the Frankish leader  Charlemagne  (  ?742–814 ), who in  800  established himself as Holy Roman Emperor. His name (Latin <i>Carolus Magnus</i>) means ‘Charles the Great’. <i>Carolus</i>—or <i>Karl</i>, the German form—was a common name among Frankish leaders, including Charlemagne's grandfather  Charles Martel  (  688–741 ). <i>Charles</i> is the French form. The name occurs occasionally in medieval Britain as <i>Karolus</i> or <i>Carolus</i>; it had a certain vogue in West Yorkshire from the 1400s, particularly among gentry families. The form <i>Charles</i> was chosen by  Mary Queen  of Scots (  1542–87 ), who had been brought up in France, for her son, <i>Charles James</i> (  1566–1625 ), who became  King James VI  of Scotland and, from  1603 ,  James I  of England. His son and grandson both reigned as  King Charles , and the name thus became established in the 17th century both in the Stuart royal house and among English and Scottish supporters of the Stuart monarchy. In the 18th century it was to some extent favoured, along with   James  , by Jacobites, supporters of the exiled Stuarts, opposed to the Hanoverian monarchy, especially in the Highlands of Scotland. In the 19th century the popularity of the name was further enhanced by romanticization of the story of ‘Bonnie Prince Charlie’, leader of the  1745  rebellion."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Fortescue","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): nickname from Old French <i>fort</i> ‘strong’ + <i>escu</i> ‘shield’.","History: A family of this name claim descent from Radulfus Fortescu who is recorded in Domesday Book (1086) as holding lands at Modbury (Devon)."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Charles Fortescue Higgins was born in 1483, in Herefordshire, England, United Kingdom, his father, Si